<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08048d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08048d">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08048d"> 48(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> systematised exaggeration</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">On ne confondra pas l&apos;&eacute;criture naturelle avec l&apos;&eacute;criture simple. L&apos;association des deux esp&egrave;ces est fr&eacute;quente, non pas n&eacute;cessaire. Sans farder la nature on peut manifester des qualit&eacute;s oppos&eacute;es &agrave; la simplicit&eacute;, par exemple: de l&apos;exag&eacute;ration et de la fantaisie. Mais il y a un moment o&ugrave; <mark>l&apos;exag&eacute;ration</mark> et la fantaisie d&eacute;truisent le naturel, c&apos;est quand elles se <mark>syst&eacute;matisent</mark>. Alors commence l&apos;&eacute;criture artificielle. <br><font color="green">[We should not confuse natural writing with simple writing. The association of the two is common, but not necessary. Without embellishing nature we may exhibit qualities that are the opposite of simplicity, for example: exaggeration and whim. But there is always a moment when exaggeration and whim destroy the natural, that is, when they become systematic. This is where artificial writing begins.]</font> <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 275</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
